            <div class="section">
                <h2>Gameplay Tips</h2>

                <div class="tip-card">
                    <strong>Esu's Heirloom is the entire build.</strong>
                    <p>Without Esu's Heirloom, Frozen Orb has too much downtime. The boots' CDR on crit is the only way to maintain consistent cast frequency. Do not attempt this build without them.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="tip-card">
                    <strong>Stack Crit Chance aggressively.</strong>
                    <p>More crits mean more Esu's Heirloom procs. Every point of Crit Chance directly translates to more Frozen Orb casts. Aim for 60%+ total Crit Chance.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="tip-card">
                    <strong>Piercing Cold is non-negotiable.</strong>
                    <p>Aspect of Piercing Cold is what transforms Frozen Orb into a screen-clearing nuke. Without it, the build lacks the coverage needed for high-tier content. This aspect is mandatory.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="tip-card">
                    <strong>Abuse permanent freeze for safety.</strong>
                    <p>Frozen enemies cannot attack. With constant Frozen Orb casts and Frost Nova, you can maintain near-permanent crowd control. Play aggressively knowing enemies are locked down.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="tip-card">
                    <strong>Manage Mana carefully.</strong>
                    <p>Frozen Orb is expensive. Stack Mana Regeneration and use Ring of Starless Skies to reduce costs. Frigid Breeze passive helps sustain, but heavy spam can still drain you dry.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="tip-card">
                    <strong>Angle your orbs for maximum impact.</strong>
                    <p>Frozen Orb travels in a line before exploding. Position and aim to maximize the explosion coverage across packs. Poor angles waste damage &mdash; good angles clear entire screens.</p>
